sect2.para:
Individuals vary in their reporting of their symptoms, with some minimizing and others amplifying their anxiety and avoidance. This variation depends in part upon the context of the assessment and in part upon the individual’s prior experiences with regard to reporting behavior. In primary care settings, anxiety disorders often go undetected (Vermani et al.,
            2011
         ) and so are often left untreated (Kroenke et al., 
            2007
         ). People seeking help for anxiety problems are typically eager for the clinician to understand and appreciate the extent of their suffering and distress, and thus may readily describe the most problematic aspects of their experience and behavior. Alternatively, it is not unusual for individuals to feel embarrassed or ashamed about their overt and covert gross motor behaviors. Ambivalence about seeking help is common, and individuals can have limited awareness of some of their symptoms (i. e., safety behaviors, threat perceptions, etc.).

The assessment of the symptoms of anxiety disorders is complicated by the fact that the assessment process relies upon questions that can serve as controlling stimuli; questions about fear cues and triggers can evoke fear responses. For example, asking an individual if they are particularly afraid of snakes evokes mental images of snakes. Those images might lead the individual to request that the clinician stop using the “s-word” (i. e., not use the word “snake”). This observation is often relevant when working with individuals who experience severe social anxiety because the questions used in the assessment create demands on the individual. This analysis suggests that clinicians should do what they can to create a non-threatening environment, especially for individuals with social anxiety. There is some evidence that building rapport with individuals with social anxiety requires a more business-like and matter-of-fact approach, rather than an overly warm and friendly approach (Valentiner & Skowronski,
            2004
         ). Clinicians should be vigilant for fear responses during the assessment process and should use their observations about the triggers of those fear responses to inform diagnostic decisions.

The increase in the prevalence of mental health concerns, including anxiety, over the past 20 years (Goodwin et al., 
            2020
         ) is not well understood (Foulkes & Andrews, 
            2023
         ). This increase is likely related to the social processes, the consequences of reporting, and the cultural meaning of symptoms (Haslam, 
            2016
         ). Interviewers should appreciate the intersubjectivity of the social process that we call the clinical interview and consider whether they are inadvertently reinforcing behaviors that maintain fear responses and avoidance.
